    <bioghist>
      <head>Biographical/Historical Information</head>
      <p>Richmond Croom Beatty (1905-1961) professor and writer,
         usually associated with Vanderbilt University, Nashville,
         Tennessee, was the author of biographies of Bayard Taylor
         (1936), Lord Macaulay (1938), and James Russell Lowell (1942);
         edited The American Tradition in Literature (1957); also wrote
         poetry, articles and reviews.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent>
      <head>Scope and Content Information</head>
      <p>Correspondence with publishers and friends, manuscripts of
         articles, poems, books, reviews, and other writings, notes,
         teaching notebooks, term papers, clippings, printed materials,
         and photographs. Includes translation from the German version
         of William Byrd's Natural History of Virginia, which Beatty
         edited and published. Correspondents include Stringfellow
         Barr, Louise Cowan, Wilbur Cross, Harold M. Jones, Merrill
         Moore, Jesse Stuart and R.M. Weaver. Also donated were
         approximately 215 books, the majority about or by southern
         writers, especially Tennesseeans. Some of the volumes are
         inscribed by the authors to Beatty. The majority of Beatty's
         own works are in the collection and autographed. A list of the
         titles donated is included at the end of the guide.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement>
      <head>Arrangement</head>
        <p>These papers are divided into two series: Series 1: Personal Papers, 1925-1960 and Series 2: Publications 1932-1967.</p>
        <p>Files are arranged topically within each series.</p>
    </arrangement>
